, but also explores and evaluates new metrics more applicable to the evolving technologies of information access.Beyond Broadband Access brings together a stellar array of media policy scholars from a wide range of disciplines-economics, law, policy studies, computer science, information science, and communications studies. Importantly, it provides a well-rounded, international perspective on theoretical approaches to databased communications policymaking in the Americas, Europe, Asia, and Africa. Showcasing a diversity of approaches, this invaluable collection helps to meet myriad challenges to improving the foundations for communications policy development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBroadband communication systems. 0aTelecommunication policy. 4aBroadband. 4abroadband access. 4adigital divide. 4ainformation and communication technology (ict). 4ainformation society. 4ametrics. 4apolicy. 4auniversal service. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aSchejter, Amit M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTaylor, Richard D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823252084zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823252084423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823252084.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK